# Next.js Senior Engineering Rules — TenderPaws Multi-Vendor

## 0) Mandatory Project Understanding
- Before coding: inspect the existing project structure, app/router usage, feature organization, shared components, hooks, services, state management, API patterns, and styling system.
- Reuse existing components, utilities, hooks, services, and design system elements before creating new ones.
- Extend existing features instead of duplicating implementations.
- Respect current project architecture and conventions; adapt only when necessary without breaking consistency.
- Read `src/styles/tokens.css` before touching any color, spacing, or typography — tokens are the source of truth, not your memory.

---

## 1) Architecture Baseline
- Follow Feature-First architecture + Clean Code + SOLID principles.
- Organize code by feature/domain, not by generic file type.
- Keep shared cross-feature logic in `src/shared/`, `src/components/`, `src/lib/`, or `src/core/` as appropriate.
- Keep feature-specific logic inside `src/features/<feature-name>/`.
- Prefer modular, scalable folder structures that support growth.

**TenderPaws feature domains:**
- `vendor` — registration, profile, store setup, account status
- `products` — add/edit/delete products, stock, category, images
- `orders` — vendor order view, status updates, admin order monitoring
- `marketplace` — multi-vendor browse/filter display (buyer-side, mobile-only; admin visibility only on web)
- `admin` — vendor approval/suspension, centralized product/order visibility
- `financials` — earnings visibility, commission architecture, payout data
- `auth` — Firebase auth, role detection (admin vs vendor)

---

## 2) Layer Responsibilities
Every feature follows this four-layer separation. Never mix layers in one file.

```
src/features/<feature>/
  presentation/     ← pages, layouts, UI components, client interactions
  application/      ← orchestration, use cases, server actions, feature services
  domain/           ← types, entities, interfaces, business rules
  infrastructure/   ← Firebase calls, API clients, repository implementations
```

- **Presentation**: renders UI, reacts to state, handles user events. No Firebase, no business rules.
- **Application**: orchestrates domain + infrastructure. No direct UI rendering.
- **Domain**: pure types and contracts. No imports from presentation or infrastructure.
- **Infrastructure**: the only layer that talks to Firebase, external APIs, or storage. Never imported directly by presentation.

**Firebase rule (hard):** Firebase imports (`firebase/firestore`, `firebase/auth`, etc.) are only allowed inside `src/features/<feature>/infrastructure/` or `src/lib/firebase.ts`. Never import Firebase in components, pages, hooks, or application layer files.

---

## 3) Next.js App Router Conventions
- Use `src/app/` with App Router conventions: `page.tsx`, `layout.tsx`, `loading.tsx`, `error.tsx`, `route.ts`.
- **Server Components by default.** Add `"use client"` only when needed: browser APIs, local state, effects, event handlers, or Firebase auth listeners.
- Keep route files minimal — delegate all UI and logic to feature modules.
- Avoid turning large subtrees into client components unnecessarily.
- Use `loading.tsx` at the route level for skeleton fallbacks (never `CircularProgress` or spinner for page/section content).

---

## 4) UI Composition Pattern
Use **Page → Section → Component** strictly.

- **Pages** (`page.tsx`): composition only. Import sections, pass server-fetched data. Zero business logic.
- **Sections**: connect data/state to UI, prepare view models, coordinate between components. One responsibility per section.
- **Components**: pure and reusable UI driven by props only. No direct data fetching, no Firebase, no application logic.

Never write large inline JSX blocks; extract into named components with their own files. No `_buildHeader()` style helper functions for large UI blocks inside pages — extract them to separate component files.

---

## 5) Design Tokens — Single Source of Truth
All brand values live in `src/styles/tokens.css` as CSS custom properties. This is mandatory — no exceptions.

**What belongs in tokens.css:**
- Brand colors (primary purple, accent tones, semantic success/error/warning/info)
- Neutral grays (background, surface, border, muted text)
- Typography scale (font families, sizes, weights, line heights)
- Spacing scale (4px base, multiples: 4/8/12/16/24/32/48/64/96px)
- Border radius scale (sm/md/lg/xl/full)
- Shadow scale (sm/md/lg)
- Z-index scale
- Transition durations

**Rules:**
- Never hardcode hex values, pixel values belonging to the scale, or font names in component files.
- Always reference `var(--token-name)` in CSS Modules or inline styles.
- When adding a new semantic color (e.g. vendor-active status green), add it to `tokens.css` first, then use it.
- Do not create local `const COLOR = '#...'` values in component files.

